05656nam a2200865Ia 9780271094083DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20232023pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710940837 a10.1515/97802710940832doi  a(DE-B1597)665205  a(OCoLC)1390441387  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aN6502.5b.S65 2023 7aART0151102bisacsh04a709.809/04223/eng/202307271 aSolomons, Delia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCold War in the White Cube :bU.S. Exhibitions of Latin American Art, 1959–1968 /cDelia Solomons. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (244 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRefiguring Modernism00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Eagle Surveys the Hemisphere -- t2 World Picturing in the Carnegie and Guggenheim Internationals -- t3 Contending for the New in New Art of Brazil and New Art of Argentina -- t4 MoMA’s “War-Time Enthusiasm for Latin America” -- tConclusion: 1968 -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1959, the very year the Cuban Revolution amplified Cold War tensions in the Americas, museumgoers in the United States witnessed a sudden surge in major exhibitions of Latin American art. Surveying the 1960s boom of such exhibits, this book documents how art produced in regions considered susceptible to communist influence was staged on U.S. soil for U.S. audiences.Held in high-profile venues such as the Guggenheim Museum, the Walker Art Center, MoMA, and the Art Institute of Chicago, the exhibitions of the 1960s Latin American art boom did not define a single stylistic trend or the art of a single nation but rather attempted to frame Latin America as a unified whole for U.S. audiences. Delia Solomons calls attention to disruptive artworks that rebelled against the curatorial frames purporting to hold them and reveals these exhibitions to be complex contact zones in which competing voices collided. Ultimately, through multiple means—including choosing to exclude artworks with readily decipherable political messages and evading references to contemporary inter-American frictions—the U.S. curators who organized these shows crafted projections of Pan-American partnership and harmony, with the United States as leader, interpreter, and good neighbor, during an era of brutal U.S. interference across the Americas.Theoretically sophisticated and highly original, this survey of Cold War–era Latin American art exhibits sheds light on the midcentury history of major U.S. art museums and makes an important contribution to the fields of museum studies, art history, and Latin American modernist art.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aArt museumsxExhibitionszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aArtxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aArt, Latin Americany20th centuryxExhibitions. 0aCold WarxInfluence. 7aART / History / Contemporary (1945-).2bisacsh  a1960s.  aAmerican art museums.  aCold war.  aLatin American art exhibits.  aNeoconcretism.  aSolomon R. Guggenheim Museum.  aWalker Art Center.  aabstraction.  aassemblage.  acommunism.  acontemporary art.  acuratorial practices.  aexhibition history.  ainter-American relations.  akineticism.  aneofiguration.  apolitics.  aproto-conceptual art.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2023z9783111318103oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2023 Englishz978311131903208iTitle is part of eBook packa